      "\n  - For any `p : { p : PersistenceSubmodule M | p ∈ I.carrier }`, `(p : PersistenceSubmodule M) c = p.val c`.\n  - Therefore, `⨆ p : { p : PersistenceSubmodule M | p ∈ I.carrier }, (p : PersistenceSubmodule M) c` is exactly `⨆ p ∈ I.carrier, p c`, because the subtype is exactly `I.carrier`.\n  - But `(sSup I.carrier) c = ⊤ c` (because `sSup I.carrier = ⊤`).\n  - But `(sSup I.carrier) c = ⨆ p ∈ I.carrier, p c` (by definition of `sSup` for `PersisteceSubmodule M`).\n  - Therefore, `⨆ p ∈ I.carrier, p c = ⊤`, as desired.\n\nHowever, it is tricky to translate this into Lean, because Lean uses `sSup` internally to define `⨆` (as a special case).\n\nAlternatively, perhaps we should use the fact that `⨆ p ∈ I.carrier, p c = ⊤`, and recognize that `⨆ p, ↑p c` is the same as `⨆ p ∈ I.carrier, p c`.\n\nBut perhaps in Lean:\n   - `⨆ p : { p : PersistenceSubmodule M | p ∈ I.carrier }, (p : PersistenceSubmodule M) c = ⨆ p",
